    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This Nature Physics paper claims to have found the clearest experimental evidence yet that electrons in exceptionally pure graphene near the charge-neutral point behave like a quantum fluid obeying universal laws predicted by relativistic physics\u2014including a striking 200-fold violation of a classical heat-transport rule and a viscosity close to a theoretical minimum set by quantum mechanics. The review board finds the work potentially significant: the experimental approach (simultaneously measuring both electrical and thermal transport in the same ultraclean device) is a genuine advance over prior work, and multiple independent devices show consistent behavior. The most important unresolved caveat is whether heat flowing through the boron-nitride substrate has been properly separated from the electronic signal, since an error there would inflate the headline number. Because the full paper and supplementary methods are behind a paywall, reviewers could not directly audit the key quantitative claims.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper reports combined DC electrical and thermal (noise-thermometry) transport in hBN-encapsulated graphene across the Dirac point, claiming: (1) the intrinsic quantum-critical conductivity \u03c3_Q converges to a quantized universal value; (2) \u03c3 and \u03ba satisfy the relativistic hydrodynamic relation expected from the Hartnoll\u2013Kovtun\u2013M\u00fcller\u2013Sachdev framework; (3) L/L_WF exceeds 200 at low temperature near the Dirac point; and (4) \u03b7/s approaches the AdS/CFT (KSS) viscosity bound within a factor of four in the cleanest devices. The review board's access was restricted to the abstract, figure/extended-data captions, and reference list. Objections that survived cross-review concern: phonon/hBN thermal background subtraction as the dominant systematic for the WF claim; residual charge inhomogeneity (puddles) potentially mimicking a quantized conductivity plateau; slip-versus-no-slip boundary-condition sensitivity in the absolute viscosity extraction; and the need for explicit quantitative differentiation from Gallagher et al. (Science 2019, ref. 15), which already targeted quantum-critical conductivity in graphene. All objections are conditional on full-text access."
    }
